{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nThe `rebar metrics` subcommand: parses `--since/--until` and optional `--bucket day|week|month`, renders the full registry over the range as JSON (default) or a text summary, and is the single entry point wiring the readers.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/_commands/metrics.py` — new: arg parsing + render loop over `src/rebar/metrics/registry.py`.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` — wire the `metrics` read subcommand: add `metrics` to a reads-with-init grouping (it reads the initialized store, like the other read commands) AND add an explicit `if sub == \"metrics\":` arm in `_dispatch()` that imports `rebar._commands.metrics` and calls its entry point (mirroring how `init`/`scratch` have dedicated arms). No existing frozenset alone routes it — the dedicated dispatch arm is required so `rebar metrics <args>` reaches the new command handler.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/metrics.txt` — new help text.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/overview.txt` — add the `metrics` line to the subcommand overview.\n- `tests/golden/cli_help/*.out` — regenerate the overview snapshots (`__overview_help.out`, `__overview_dashhelp.out`) and add `metrics__help.out`, since the subcommand set is enumerated there.\n- `docs/cli-reference.md` — do NOT hand-edit: it is GENERATED by `scripts/gen_cli_reference.py` (with a CI drift gate). After adding the `metrics` help/overview text, REGENERATE it (`python scripts/gen_cli_reference.py`) and commit the regenerated file so the drift gate passes. Its content is driven by the help text, not edited directly.\n- `tests/interfaces/test_metrics_cli.py` — new CLI subprocess test.\n\n## Approach\nA thin CLI over the registry keeps the command complete-once: it builds a **context object** and calls `rebar.metrics.registry.evaluate(spec, context)` for every `MetricSpec`, emitting value-or-`unavailable` per metric, so new signals appear with no CLI change.\n\n**REGISTRY hydration (import the PACKAGE, not just registry):** `REGISTRY` is only fully populated after the reader modules run their registration side-effects, and those imports live in `src/rebar/metrics/__init__.py` (which imports `event_metrics`, `git_metrics`, `sidecar_metrics`). Importing `rebar.metrics.registry` ALONE does not trigger them. So `metrics.py` must `import rebar.metrics` (the package — running its `__init__`, which hydrates `REGISTRY` with every reader's specs) and then read `rebar.metrics.registry.REGISTRY`. This does NOT breach the adapter-isolation rule: `__init__.py` imports the reader modules but NOT `rebar.metrics.adapters.*`, so the optional CI/transcript adapters are never pulled in.\n\n**The context object (the contract the readers already expect):** every reader's registered `compute` is a single-arg callable that reads `ctx.repo_root`, `ctx.since`, `ctx.until` (via `getattr(ctx, \"repo_root\", None)` etc. — see the git/event/sidecar readers). So `metrics.py` constructs a small context (a dataclass or `SimpleNamespace`) carrying exactly `repo_root` (the resolved store root), `since`, and `until` (the parsed range), and passes it to `evaluate`. For `--bucket`, it builds one context per bucket sub-range and evaluates the registry per bucket, keying the output by bucket.\n\n**Adapter isolation (portability guard from 1f77/538c):** `metrics.py` reaches metrics only through `rebar.metrics.registry` (and the package import that populates `REGISTRY`); it must NOT import any `rebar.metrics.adapters` module. Because that adapters package may not exist yet at this point in the stack, the guard is a **source-level scan**: the test reads `src/rebar/_commands/metrics.py` and asserts its source contains no `rebar.metrics.adapters` import (a text/AST check that holds regardless of whether the package exists). Adapter-backed metrics reach the command only through `REGISTRY`, never a direct import — so the core command stays harness-agnostic.\n\nRegistering a subcommand touches the enumerated help/golden surfaces (`overview.txt` + the `tests/golden/cli_help` snapshots), which are regenerated to match, and the GENERATED `docs/cli-reference.md` (regenerated via `scripts/gen_cli_reference.py`, never hand-edited — a CI drift gate enforces this) — all part of the edit set. Read-only; `--bucket day|week|month` splits the `[since, until]` range into sub-ranges and evaluates the registry once per sub-range (each reader already accepts `since`/`until` as ISO date bounds — the command does not reach into HLC timestamps itself; the readers do their own timestamp filtering).\n\n**Output formats.** JSON (default) is the machine contract: `{\"since\",\"until\",\"metrics\": {<id>: {\"lens\",\"source\",\"confidence\",\"value\"} | {\"unavailable\": {\"reason\",\"accruing_since\"}}, ...}}`. `--output text` is a deterministic human summary — one line per metric in registry order: `<id>  [<lens>/<source>]  <value-or-\"unavailable: <reason>\">` (a fixed-width, self-defined layout — NOT borrowed from `rebar audit`, whose schema is structurally different); an `unavailable` metric renders as `unavailable: <reason>`. Both formats include every registered metric id.\n\n## Tests\n- CLI (real subprocess against a temp store): `rebar metrics --since ... --until ... --output json` exits 0 and emits a `metrics` map containing every registered id; an unpopulated metric shows `unavailable`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/interfaces/test_metrics_cli.py` passes: `rebar metrics --since 2026-01-01 --until 2026-07-01 --output json` exits 0 and the emitted `.metrics` map contains an entry for EVERY id in `rebar.metrics.registry.REGISTRY` (the test asserts `set(output[\"metrics\"].keys()) >= {s.id for s in REGISTRY}` — NOT merely `length > 0`), each entry being either a value (with `source`+`confidence`) or an `unavailable` object.\n- [ ] the portability guard holds: a test asserts `src/rebar/_commands/metrics.py` does not import `rebar.metrics.adapters` (the core command stays harness-agnostic; adapter-backed metrics arrive only via `REGISTRY`).\n- [ ] `rebar metrics --help` renders the help file and the command is listed by bare `rebar` — CLI test asserts exit 0 and help contains `--since`.\n- [ ] the golden CLI-help snapshots are regenerated and the `tests/golden/cli_help` suite passes with `metrics` listed.\n- [ ] `--bucket week` yields a per-bucket series for a metric with history — CLI test asserts the JSON contains at least one bucket key."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784456343802975001,"uuid":"85a80fa0-fabc-4057-b279-4884cb6d5c67"}